<h2 id=3D"introduction">Introduction</h2>
<p>Recently I had an idea of a project which requires using the Bluetooth A=
PI. I wanted to create something simple and did not want to use UWP for 2 r=
easons:</p>
<ol>
<li>I wanted to have a tray icon. This is also possible with UWP but creati=
ng a full-trust application seemed way more complicated for my scenario.</l=
i>
<li>I wanted a simple self-contained application which can run without the =
need of enabling developer mode for the end users.</li>
</ol>
<h2 id=3D"how-to-use-ble-classes-with-wpf">How to Use BLE Classes with WPF<=
/h2>
<p>My framework of choice for the project was WPF. There was only 1 problem=
, the BLE classes were not available. After a lot of research and failed at=
tempts there is actually a way to use them with WPF. Here is what I did:</p=
>
<h3 id=3D"1-install-windows-sdk">1. Install Windows SDK</h3>
<p>First thing first you have to install the <a href=3D"https://developer.m=
icrosoft.com/en-us/windows/downloads/windows-10-sdk/">Windows SDK.</a> Idea=
lly you want to install it in its default location since you cannot change =
it later. Believe me I=E2=80=99ve tried!</p>
<p>If you installed it in a different location, you cannot use it with UWP =
and the Visual Studio for creating for example Full-Trust applications. I=
=E2=80=99ve also tried that one too.</p>
<p>The SDK will give you the <strong>Windows.winmd</strong> file. If you wa=
nt to learn more check out <a href=3D"https://stackoverflow.com/questions/5=
4375771/how-to-read-a-winmd-winrt-metadata-file#:~:text=3DA%20WinMD%20is%20=
a%20binary,in%20a%20native%20WinRT%20dll.&amp;text=3DThe%20Windows%20Runtim=
e%20is%20exposed,framework%20(Ecma%2D335).">How to read a winmd (WinRT meta=
data file).</a> <a href=3D"https://stackoverflow.com/users/12597/ian-boyd">=
Ian Boyd</a> explained it in great detail. There is also the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/uwp/winrt-cref/winmd-files">official document=
ation</a></p>
<h3 id=3D"2-locate-windowswinmd-file-and-add-a-reference">2. Locate Windows=
.winmd File and Add a Reference</h3>
<p>If you followed the default location path the <strong>Windows.winmd</str=
ong> file is located in <strong>C:\Program Files (x86)\Windows Kits\10\Unio=
nMetadata\10.0.19041.0\Windows.winmd</strong>. You can go ahead and =D0=B0d=
d this file as a reference to your project.</p>
<p>Unfortunately, for me this does not work with .NET5. I tried so many thi=
ngs that if I should write them, I have to make another blog post. For this=
 example and for my project I am using .Net Core 3.1.</p>
<p>Now you can use the BLE classes with your WPF, Windows Forms, and/or Con=
sole applications. There is one catch though. You cannot use async await ye=
t.</p>
<h3 id=3D"3-fix-async-methods">3. Fix Async methods</h3>
<p>In order to use them you have to bring <strong>System.Runtime.WindowsRun=
time.dll</strong> too. If you installed .NET Framework 4 you should have it=
 in your machine. My file=E2=80=99s location is <strong>C:\Windows\Microsof=
t.NET\Framework64\v4.0.30319\System.Runtime.WindowsRuntime.dll</strong></p>
<p>After all of this, you should have a working application.</p>
<h2 id=3D"lets-create-a-ble-application">Let=E2=80=99s Create a BLE Applica=
tion</h2>
<p>For the sake of simplicity, we will create a console application.</p>
<p>Create a <strong>.NET Core 3.1</strong> Console application. Let=E2=80=
=99s call it BleConsoleDemo. We will write a simple program that catches al=
l the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bluetooth_Low_Energy">BLE</a=
> devices that emits <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bluetooth_Low=
_Energy#Advertising_and_discovery">advertising packets</a>.</p>
<p>Do not forget to add <strong>System.Runtime.WindowsRuntime.dll</strong> =
and <strong>Windows.winmd</strong> references as described above.</p>
